The project “Empowering left behind minority communities to effectively participate in the development process of Bangladesh” is aimed to empower local minority rights CSOs and networks in Bangladesh to effectively engage with left behind communities and enable their participation in local governance and development process. Duration of the project is January 2021-June 2024. The project specifically wants to build the capacity of local and national minority rights CSOs and networks and ensure a conducive and enabling environment to promote socio-economic rights and structured participation of women and girls, transgender community and people with disability.

3 implementing organisations (Islamic Relief, Hurras, Basmeh & Zeitooneh) and 2 supporting organisations (CAFOD, Christian Aid) will collaborate to develop a range of products and services to enhance the indigenous approaches to safeguarding within the education sector in Northwest Syria (NWS) Focusing on Children, and to provide a roadmap for international organisations to utilise in future DEC appeals to invest in a decolonial approach to safeguarding by identifying, and investing in the pre-existing indigenous capabilities.

The Overall Impact of the project : Violence against women (VAW) is reduced in the RMG factories, in public spaces and commute, and women’s rights to safety in the workplace are protected, Outcome 1: The workplace culture at the RMG factories is free from violence and harassment and discriminatory practices and women workers have access to psychosocial, emotional, and legal services. Outcome 2: Women workers, including most marginalized, are free from violence in public spaces and during commute. Outcome 3: Apex agencies, brands/ buyers and Government authorities are engaged in ensuring an enabling environment for gender justice, through prevention of VAW and creating gender friendly workplace as per the labour law and are accountable to stakeholders. The project will be implemented at the factory, community, and national levels.

The Enhancing Coordination for Disaster Response in Nigeria (ECoDIN) Program seeks to strengthen relevant government institutions and systems to better plan and respond to human-induced or natural disasters in selected locations in Northcentral, Nigeria. 


The main objective of the program is to enhance government capacity and systems to better manage shocks and improve coordination of disaster response.   


The outcome of the project will be improved/strengthened government systems to detect, manage, and respond to shocks in the selected states. It will be a continuous learning action that helps to transform humanitarian actions into development interventions while institutions responsible for disaster management and humanitarian responses will have their capacity enhanced for state-wide coverage and response as required.

Ce projet vise à renforcer un partenariat de confiance dans lequel les Citoyens participent à la proposition, au contrôle des politiques publiques et les PP rendent effectivement compte au niveau national et dans les 7 provinces ciblées par cette action. Pour y arriver, les produits suivants seront atteints : 
(P1) : Des cadres de dialogue et de concertation (CCNSC-CCPSC, CLPP-CLGP) fonctionnels, opérationnels et inclusifs entre PP et Citoyens, qui participent avec efficacité aux processus de Conception, Mise en œuvre et Evaluation des politiques publiques; 
(P2) : Des mécanismes accrus de redevabilité et de transparence des dirigeants inclusifs vis-à-vis des citoyens au niveau national, provincial et local; 
(P3) : Des OSC/cadres multi acteurs qui mènent des actions complémentaires à travers le soutien aux tiers (microprojets) visant le renforcement de la participation citoyenne notamment des femmes, jeunes et PVH.
A long terme, les acquis contribueront au renforcement de la représentativité et participation politique de la femme, des jeunes et des PVH, de la culture démocratique, de la responsabilité, de la transparence et de la mise en œuvre des politiques qui contribuent réellement au bien-être du peuple congolais. 
Les principales activités d’opérationnalisation des OSC et de Dialogue entre PP et citoyens/OSC 
(P1) : Appui organisationnel et institutionnel aux cadres de dialogue aux niveaux national et provincial (CCNSC et CCPSC) ainsi qu’au niveau local des ETD (CLGP et CLPP); Renforcement des compétences des OSC sur des thèmes pertinents visant à renforcer l’inclusion des femmes et des jeunes; Elaboration des cahiers des charges ; analyse des politiques ; plaidoyer ; suivi et contrôle citoyen); Proposition des politiques, basé sur des analyses participatives, basé aussi sur l’expression directe des populations locales surtout les femmes, les jeunes et toute autre couche de personnes marginalisées, à travers l’outil e-pop en collaboration avec RFI Planète. Activités de redevabilité et transparence 
(P2) : Formation des autorités et leaders des OSC sur la gouvernance et la participation citoyenne (élaboration et monitoring de budget participatif (Province et ETD), redevabilité, thèmes transversaux-Genre, Environnement, Approche basée sur les droits humains, Do no harm, No one left behind, etc.); Organisation des espaces de dialogue et d’échanges entre autorités locales et citoyens à travers des Tribunes d’expression populaire (TEP), réunions et ateliers de réflexion, débats citoyens, Hub communautaires, etc. ; Expérimentation « Prési-Gouvemètre», comme outil de monitoring de la gouvernance. Activités de subventions aux tiers 
(P3) : Accorder des micros-subventions aux OSC multi-acteurs (tiers) afin de mener des actions complémentaires contribuant à l’atteinte de l’objectif et/ou produits attendus de la présente action.

CREAW and CRAWN Trust understand that in order to have an equal society, there is need to use intersectional approaches that center the diverse needs, experiences, and leadership of people most impacted by discrimination and oppression. Such approaches are important and necessary in efforts to address gender inequality that violates women’s and girls’ rights, constrains their choices and voices and impacts negatively on their ability to fully participate in and benefit from development processes. CREAW and CRAWN Trust are therefore proposing a project that seeks to enhance gender justice by engaging religious leaders from the Side-by Side Faith Movement for Gender Justice and communities towards shifting knowledge, attitude and behaviors to promote the advancement and protection of women and girls. At the onset a baseline will be carried out to establish the nature and priority of social economic needs of women in the target counties that require intervention. Engagements will then focus on building capacity of women rights organizations as right holders to directly engage in conversations with duty bearers and religious leaders demanding accountability in preventing gender-based violence, advocate for enactment of gender responsive laws that actualize women leadership and advance efforts towards the achievement of gender equality. Capacities of duty bearers to provide emergency and recovery services as secondary prevention for survivors of gender-based violence will also be enhanced through capacity building interventions. Faith based leaders will also have their capacity enhanced to understand the challenges experienced by vulnerable women and girls and therefore use their platforms and spaces of influence to advocate for improved implementation of laws for the protection of those in crisis. In ensuring the gains of the project are sustained over time, accountability platforms will be activated to hold leaders and service providers to account on their protection mandate. In celebrating gains, the project will mark international calendar days such as 16 days of Activism, International Women’s Day and day of the African Child to highlight progress made and advocate for further action to actualize gender equality in Kenya. Interventions will use both physical and virtual platforms including media spaces for information sharing and campaigns. Key outcomes will include expanding stakeholders' voices and action towards advancing the achievement of not just equity (equal distribution of resources, access, and leadership opportunities) but also equality where men, women, boys and girls live dignified and healthier lives. The project approach is empowering by providing an opportunity for communities to define their priorities and take action towards mitigating experiences of gender inequality. This will include addressing discrimination, abuse and positive shifts in social norms towards gender-respecting communities.

ACRE: Accelerating Cooperation and Resilience to tackle natural resource challenges in fragile and conflict affected borderlands, using the Humanitarian-Development-Peacebuilding Nexus
This project will be implemented in northern Kenya and southern Ethiopia to improve the adaptive capacity of these drought prone communities and focuses primarily on Marsabit County, the largest ASAL county in Kenya as well as the Nyangatom and Dasenech districts of south Omo in Ethiopia. The geographic locations are selected considering the perennial droughts that these areas experienced by the negative impacts of climate change and due to the frequent escalation of border conflict among the pastoral communities that frequently occur as a result of competition towards the dwindling natural resources. The climate change induced prolonged droughts in the borderland area has led to population displacement, changes in the distribution of resources within society, increased gender inequalities, depleted livelihoods, and increased resources scarcity.

DEC member agencies; Christian Aid, ActionAid and CAFOD under the umbrella “The Blue Sky Initiative” in collaboration with the Syrian Civil Society Network Platform (SCNP) propose to commence a 3-stage iterative process to co-create an innovative project to accelerate localisation in the TSEQ response in collaboration with the DEC. Stage 1 will take place over 5 months from February to end June 2024, with Stage 2 taking place over 4 months (July to October 2024), with the final stage taking place across November, December and January.

Following consultations with the collective initiative members, the Human Rights Due Diligence (HRDD) Project Design Tool was presented to the DEC as the recommended initiative to pilot.  The vision for the project is that the HRDD tool will support the mainstreaming of a human rights lens during programme design, both to minimise risk in complex emergencies, as well as raise awareness of human rights frameworks, resulting in staff being more aware of the potential, and future risks, associated with human rights in complex emergencies.
